	<li class="comment even depth-2 highlander-comment" id="li-comment-2763">
		<article id="comment-2763" class="comment">
			<footer class="comment-meta">
				<div class="comment-author vcard">
					<img alt='' src='https://2.gravatar.com/avatar/b2141ccd75cf734d1db729a81dab740f?s=39&#038;d=identicon&#038;r=R' class='avatar avatar-39' height='39' width='39' /><span class="fn"><a href='http://jgoodwin.net' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Jonathan</a></span> on <a href="https://tedunderwood.com/2012/12/14/what-can-topic-models-of-pmla-teach-us-about-the-history-of-literary-scholarship/#comment-2763"><time datetime="2012-12-15T11:42:39+00:00">December 15, 2012 at 11:42 am</time></a> <span class="says">said:</span>
									</div><!-- .comment-author .vcard -->

				
			</footer>

			<div class="comment-content"><p>There is a correlated topic model variant of the LDA algorithm. I believe it&#8217;s implemented in either the &#8220;lda&#8221; or &#8220;topicmodels&#8221; R packages. I have only experimented with dynamic topic modeling, which I think is interesting to compare with time-series data from regular LDA models (that&#8217;s what John Laudun, Clai Rice, and I are doing with folklore journals in a similar project we&#8217;re working on at the moment). But I haven&#8217;t tried correlated topic modeling, which seems like it might add something to what is being discussed here.</p>
</div>

