			<div class="comment-content"><p>Andrew has included the stoplist he used in his github repository (linked above). It&#8217;s not a standard one; e.g., we include a lot of personal names but I believe we were less aggressive in subtracting common/function words than is sometimes the practice in other disciplines. I would put my stoplist up in github, except I actually made this model 4 months ago, and I&#8217;ve been adding to the stoplist since then, so it&#8217;s no longer totally accurate. E.g., you&#8217;ll see &#8220;univ.&#8221; and &#8220;trans.&#8221; in some topics, which I have since decided to stoplist-out.</p>
<p>Our stoplists were very close except that I believe Andrew did include common words in French and German, etc., in his stoplist. I didn&#8217;t. I&#8217;ve since decided that Andrew&#8217;s approach is preferable. In a multilingual corpus you want multilingual stopwords.</p>
</div>

