			<div class="comment-content"><p>@Bill, regarding the ngrams comment. I was curious how &#8216;philology&#8217; played out over the years in Literature studies in particular, using JSTOR&#8217;s DfR Literature sub-category, which is available here: <a href="http://scottbot.net/uploads/PhilLitWeingart.png" rel="nofollow">Philology ratio per year</a>. Though it&#8217;s quite a slow decline, it seems to fit your narrative.</p>
<p>It&#8217;s odd how there&#8217;s still this pervasive implicit assumption of &#8216;revolutions&#8217; (or at least punctuated equilibria) in disciplinary histories, even though slow growths and declines appear every bit as frequently. Those are harder to pack up neatly in narratives, I suppose.</p>
</div>

