	<li class="comment byuser comment-author-tedunderwood bypostauthor odd alt depth-2 highlander-comment" id="li-comment-2753">
		<article id="comment-2753" class="comment">
			<footer class="comment-meta">
				<div class="comment-author vcard">
					<img alt='' src='https://1.gravatar.com/avatar/76dd28669b8c966858940eeb24cc684a?s=39&#038;d=identicon&#038;r=R' class='avatar avatar-39' height='39' width='39' /><span class="fn"><a href='https://tedunderwood.wordpress.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>tedunderwood</a></span> on <a href="https://tedunderwood.com/2012/12/14/what-can-topic-models-of-pmla-teach-us-about-the-history-of-literary-scholarship/#comment-2753"><time datetime="2012-12-15T09:44:23+00:00">December 15, 2012 at 9:44 am</time></a> <span class="says">said:</span>
									</div><!-- .comment-author .vcard -->

				
			</footer>

			<div class="comment-content"><p>Heh. I appreciate that anecdote, Bill, because it illuminates something I didn&#8217;t understand about the model. Kemp Malone (whom I had never heard of) darn near gets his own topic: <a href="https://dl.dropbox.com/u/4713959/pmla/41.jpg" rel="nofollow">https://dl.dropbox.com/u/4713959/pmla/41.jpg</a></p>
</div>

			<div class="reply">
							</div><!-- .reply -->
		</article><!-- #comment-## -->

	<ul class="children">
	<li class="comment even depth-3 highlander-comment" id="li-comment-2779">
		<article id="comment-2779" class="comment">
			<footer class="comment-meta">
				<div class="comment-author vcard">
					<img alt='' src='https://2.gravatar.com/avatar/e01704aab56a6abc54ecaa750f98e7b5?s=39&#038;d=identicon&#038;r=R' class='avatar avatar-39' height='39' width='39' /><span class="fn"><a href='http://new-savanna.blogspot.com/' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Bill Benzon</a></span> on <a href="https://tedunderwood.com/2012/12/14/what-can-topic-models-of-pmla-teach-us-about-the-history-of-literary-scholarship/#comment-2779"><time datetime="2012-12-17T13:41:05+00:00">December 17, 2012 at 1:41 pm</time></a> <span class="says">said:</span>
									</div><!-- .comment-author .vcard -->

				
			</footer>

			<div class="comment-content"><p>@Scott “It’s odd how there’s still this pervasive implicit assumption of ‘revolutions’ (or at least punctuated equilibria) in disciplinary histories, even though slow growths and declines appear every bit as frequently. Those are harder to pack up neatly in narratives, I suppose.”</p>
<p>I wonder. I wonder how long the profession’s talked that way about itself? Certainly when structuralism and post-structuralism came roaring through there was a sense of radical change. I can imagine that that rhetoric just settled in and became the standard for talking about the profession. Anything new had to be revolutionary, otherwise it wouldn’t register. But did people talk that way before then? I don’t know.</p>
</div>

			<div class="reply">
